point that this quite fabulous

00:00:06.920 --> 00:00:09.180
about Hermitian operators.

00:00:09.180 --> 00:00:15.700
Here is the thing that it
really should impress you.

00:00:15.700 --> 00:00:22.880
It's the fact that any,
all Hermitian operators

00:00:22.880 --> 00:00:29.335
have as many eigenfunctions and
eigenvalues as you can possibly

00:00:29.335 --> 00:00:33.470
need, whatever that means.

00:00:33.470 --> 00:00:35.720
But they're rich.

00:00:35.720 --> 00:00:41.020
It's a lot of those states.

00:00:41.020 --> 00:00:49.300
What it really means is that the
set of eigenfunctions for any

00:00:49.300 --> 00:00:52.270
Hermitian operator--
whatever Hermitian operator,

00:00:52.270 --> 00:00:55.300
it's not just for some
especially nice ones--

00:00:55.300 --> 00:01:01.130
for all of them you
get eigenfunctions.

00:01:01.130 --> 00:01:06.490
And these eigenfunctions,
because it has vectors,

00:01:06.490 --> 00:01:11.230
they are enough to span
the space of states.

00:01:11.230 --> 00:01:15.130
That is any state can be
written as a superposition

00:01:15.130 --> 00:01:16.940
of those eigenvectors.

00:01:16.940 --> 00:01:18.120
There's enough.

00:01:18.120 --> 00:01:24.270
If you're thinking finite
dimensional vector spaces,

00:01:24.270 --> 00:01:28.060
if you're looking at
the Hermitian matrix,

00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:31.120
the eigenvectors
will provide you

00:01:31.120 --> 00:01:34.120
a basis for the vector space.

00:01:34.120 --> 00:01:38.340
You can understand anything
in terms of eigenvectors.

00:01:38.340 --> 00:01:40.870
It is such an important theorem.

00:01:40.870 --> 00:01:45.330
It's called the spectral
theorem in mathematics.

00:01:45.330 --> 00:01:49.870
And it's discussed in
lots of detail in 805.

00:01:49.870 --> 00:01:52.480
Because there's
a minor subtlety.

00:01:52.480 --> 00:01:56.190
We can get the whole
idea about it here.

00:01:56.190 --> 00:01:58.750
But there are a couple
of complications

00:01:58.750 --> 00:02:00.940
that mathematicians
have to iron out.

00:02:00.940 --> 00:02:06.100
So basically let's
state we really

00:02:06.100 --> 00:02:08.370
need, which is the following.

00:02:08.370 --> 00:02:26.581
Consider the collection of
eigenfunctions and eigenvalues

00:02:26.581 --> 00:02:34.130
of the Hermitian operator q.

00:02:34.130 --> 00:02:43.380
And then I go and say, well,
q psi 1 equal q 1 psi 1 q psi

