00:09:21.900 --> 00:09:31.530
or just moving one to one side,
integral psi i star psi j dx

00:09:31.530 --> 00:09:34.550
is equal to 0.

00:09:34.550 --> 00:09:37.350
So look what you've proven
by using Hermiticity,

00:09:37.350 --> 00:09:41.410
that the difference
between the eigenvalues

00:09:41.410 --> 00:09:47.520
times the overlap between
psi i and psi j must be 0.

00:09:47.520 --> 00:09:49.800
But we started
with the assumption

00:09:49.800 --> 00:09:52.970
that the eigenvalues
are different.

00:09:52.970 --> 00:09:55.780
And if the eigenvalues are
different, this is non-zero.

00:09:55.780 --> 00:09:59.810
And the only possibility
is that this integral is 0.

00:09:59.810 --> 00:10:03.190
So this implies
since we've assumed

00:10:03.190 --> 00:10:08.310
that qi is different than qj.

00:10:08.310 --> 00:10:17.740
We've proven that psi i
star psi j dx is equal to 0.

00:10:17.740 --> 00:10:20.960
And that's part of
this little theorem.

00:10:20.960 --> 00:10:24.740
That the eigenfunctions
can be organized

00:10:24.740 --> 00:10:28.580
to have orthonormality
and orthonormality

00:10:28.580 --> 00:10:31.510
between the different points.

00:10:31.510 --> 00:10:32.980
My proof is good.

00:10:32.980 --> 00:10:36.470
But it's not perfect.

00:10:36.470 --> 00:10:40.750
Because it ignores one
possible complication,

00:10:40.750 --> 00:10:47.580
which is that here we wrote the
list of all the eigenfunctions.

00:10:47.580 --> 00:10:50.550
But sometimes something
very interesting

00:10:50.550 --> 00:10:52.770
happens in quantum mechanics.

00:10:52.770 --> 00:10:55.490
It's called degeneracy.

00:10:55.490 --> 00:10:58.710
And degeneracy
means that there may

00:10:58.710 --> 00:11:05.220
be several eigenfunctions
that are different but have

00:11:05.220 --> 00:11:06.766
the same eigenvalue.

00:11:09.940 --> 00:11:12.210
We're going to find that soon--

00:11:12.210 --> 00:11:14.220
we're going to find,
for example, states

00:11:14.220 --> 00:11:18.880
of a particle that move in
a circle that are different

00:11:18.880 --> 00:11:20.260
and have the same energy.

00:11:20.260 --> 00:11:23.560
For example, a particle moving
in a circle with this velocity

00:11:23.560 --> 00:11:27.530
and a particle moving in a
circle with the same magnitude

00:11:27.530 --> 00:11:30.440
of the velocity in
the other direction

00:11:30.440 --> 00:11:35.250
are two states that
are different but have

00:11:35.250 --> 00:11:39.040
the same energy eigenvalue.

00:11:39.040 --> 00:11:42.440
So it's possible that this
list not all are different.

00:11:42.440 --> 00:11:47.050
So suppose you have like three
or four degenerate states,

00:11:47.050 --> 00:11:49.420
say three degenerate states.

00:11:49.420 --> 00:11:51.930
They all have the
same eigenvalue.

00:11:51.930 --> 00:11:53.330
But they are different.

00:11:53.330 --> 00:11:57.070
Are they orthonormal or not?

00:11:57.070 --> 00:12:06.046
The answer is-- actually
the clue is there.

00:12:06.046 --> 00:12:11.940
The eigenfunctions can
be organized to satisfy.

00:12:11.940 --> 00:12:16.340
It would be wrong if you say
the eigenfunctions satisfy.

00:12:16.340 --> 00:12:19.260
They can be
organized to satisfy.

00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:25.620
It means that, yes, those ones
that have different eigenvalues

00:12:25.620 --> 00:12:28.063
are automatically orthonormal.

00:12:28.063 --> 00:12:32.130
But those that have
the same eigenvalues,

00:12:32.130 --> 00:12:35.440
you may have three
of them maybe,

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:37.990
they may not necessarily
be orthonormal.

00:12:37.990 --> 00:12:43.490
But you can do linear
transformations of them

00:12:43.490 --> 00:12:48.010
and form linear combinations
such that they are orthonormal.

00:12:48.010 --> 00:12:51.070
So the interesting
part of this theorem,

00:12:51.070 --> 00:12:54.070
which is the more difficult
part mathematically,

00:12:54.070 --> 00:12:57.370
is to show that when
you have degeneracies

00:12:57.370 --> 00:12:59.750
this still can be done.

00:12:59.750 --> 00:13:06.100
And there's still enough
eigenvectors to span the space.

